There's a problem with GCHandle.Alloc where if you try to allocate the same object (in my case the same byte array) with the GCHandle.Pinned parameter, it doesn't store the byte array again and instead just uses a reference to the first byte array that was stored.

Here's an example

```csharp
var bytes = new byte[] { 0x00, 0xFF, 0x00, 0xFF };

var buffer1 = GCHandle.Alloc(bytes, GCHandleType.Pinned);

var buffer1Address = buffer1.AddrOfPinnedObject();

var buffer2 = GCHandle.Alloc(bytes, GCHandleType.Pinned);

var buffer2Address = buffer2.AddrOfPinnedObject();
```

In this case, buffer1Address and buffer2Address will be the exact same.

I was just wondering if this is intentional or if it is indeed a bug?

If this is intentional maybe offering an option to not do this could be useful (at least in my case it is)

